Backend: architecture and conventions

Rules for everything under backend/. Longer rationale lives in backend/docs/architecture/. When code and this file disagree, this file wins — change the code.

How to change backend code

Prefer the smallest change that actually fixes the right place. Before adding anything new: is this change needed, or does an existing path already cover it? Is the same helper, pattern, or module already in the repo — reuse it. Can stdlib or an existing util do it — use that. Can it stay in one place (shared function, one guard) instead of copies at every call site? Only then write the minimum that works.

Read the request and follow the real call path end to end before picking where to edit. A tiny patch on the wrong layer is still wrong.

Fix the shared root, not each symptom. If a function is broken, grep its callers and put the guard once where the invariant belongs. Patching only the ticket’s path leaves the sibling path broken.

Do not invent abstractions, layers, or packages nobody asked for. Do not add a dependency if stdlib or an existing package is enough. Prefer deleting and reusing over adding. Prefer the boring obvious path. Touch as few files as possible once you know the right place. When two solutions are the same size, pick the one that handles edge cases correctly — short is not the same as fragile. If a request looks oversized, ask whether a thinner existing path already covers it. If you knowingly leave a known ceiling (global lock, O(n²) scan, naive heuristic), mark it with a short comment naming the ceiling and how to upgrade later.

Never skimp on: understanding the flow before editing, validation at trust boundaries (HTTP/API), errors that would lose data, security, and anything the task explicitly requires. Non-trivial logic needs one small runnable check that fails if the logic breaks (usually a domain or use-case test). Trivial one-liners need none.

1. Dependency rules

cmd → application, infrastructure, utils, domain (only place for DI).
application/** → domain/**, utils/** (not infrastructure, not cmd, not another application module).
domain/** → stdlib and domain/shared/** only.
infrastructure → domain/**, utils/** (implements domain ports/repositories).
utils/** → stdlib, general-purpose libs, and domain/shared/errors.go only.

Domain imports nothing from HTTP, pgx, SDKs, application, infrastructure, or utils. Put external talk behind a port.

Application never imports infrastructure. Use cases take interfaces in the constructor; cmd/<module>/main.go wires the implementations.

Infrastructure implements domain interfaces and does not know about application.

Utils sit at the bottom: everyone may use them; they use none of our layers. One narrow exception: utils/httpx/errors.go may import domain/shared/errors.go (sentinels only) to map them to HTTP codes. Nothing else from domain may enter utils.

domain/shared/ports/* may use domain/shared/vo/*, but not concrete bounded contexts.

Layer boundary — do not put code in the wrong place

Each layer holds only its own job. If something feels convenient to drop “nearby”, stop and put it where the dependency rules say it belongs.

Use case (Execute): orchestration and I/O only — load, call a port/repo, hand data to domain, persist, return. No SQL, no HTTP/JSON shaping, no prompt text, no business transforms (for/switch that builds domain meaning), no new external-system contracts. Ports for LLM, storage, email, payments and the like live in domain/shared/ports/; repository contracts live in domain/<ctx>/repository.go. The use case receives those interfaces in the constructor and calls them — it does not declare the port next to the use case.

Domain: invariants, entities, policies, pure input→output functions, repository interfaces, domain errors, domain text (prompts). No utils (timex helpers beyond what domain/shared allows, httpx, database, pagination, auth wiring, logging packages — none of these). Domain imports stdlib and domain/shared only. If you need a clock or ID, pass now / use vo.NewID(); do not pull utils into domain to “make it easier”.

Repository (infrastructure implementation): persistence only — SQL, mapping Model↔Entity inside the infra layer, transactions as storage mechanics. No business rules, no policies, no calling LLM/HTTP APIs, no scenario branching that belongs in a use case or domain.

Common smells to reject on sight: a Port/Client interface defined inside use_cases/; import of internal/utils inside domain/**; domain logic or prompt building inside a repository; HTTP DTO fields or Huma tags leaking into domain or use-case commands.

2. Module layout (internal/application/<module>/)

Every module looks the same:

internal/application/<module>/
  api/endpoints.go — Huma registration, all routes in one file
  api/schema.go — Input/Output DTOs
  api/mapper.go — DTO ↔ use-case command/result
  use_cases/ — package usecases, one file per scenario; <action>.go is <Action>UseCase with a single Execute
  worker/ — ticker / cron / consumer, own folder next to api
  config.go
  module.go — Mount/New: DI, use cases, api.Register, middleware

Packages: module root is <module>, api/ is api, use_cases/ is usecases.

Any background loop (scheduler, worker, consumer, subscriber) lives in worker/, never inside a use case. The loop reacts to ctx.Done() and calls work through a use case Execute.

3. Domain (internal/domain/<ctx>/)

One bounded context = one folder = one package. Depends only on stdlib and domain/shared.

Entities — identity plus behavior. Change state through verb methods (UpdateInfo, Cancel), not bare setters that skip invariants.

Aggregates — roots that keep the graph consistent; change children only through the root.

Value objects — no identity (Money, Email); validation lives in the constructor so an invalid value cannot exist. Shared VOs in domain/shared/vo/, context-specific ones inside the context.

Policies — pure “is this allowed?” functions (RequireGlobalAdmin, client.RequireWrite). No mutation.

Pure functions — see below.

Repository interface — repository.go in the same package: data access for this context.

Errors — errors.go, wrapping a shared sentinel with %w.

Domain text (e.g. LLM prompts) — part of the domain, not utils.

domain/shared/: vo/, ports/ (external systems: LLMClient, ObjectStorage, EmailSender), errors.go (base sentinels).

Repository vs port: a repository is data access for one context and lives in domain/<ctx>/. A port is an external or cross-cutting system and lives in domain/shared/ports/, implemented under infrastructure/adapters/. An LLM, payment, or S3 client is always a port, even if only one module uses it.

Domain vs use case: domain holds what is always true for the entity. A use case holds what is true only for one scenario. Check: if the same operation later runs from an admin panel, import, or integration, must the rule still apply? Yes → domain. No → use case.

Pure functions in domain (prefer these). Any input → output logic with no I/O belongs in domain/<ctx>/, not in a use case or utils. A pure function takes domain types (and time.Time when it needs “now”) and returns domain types, values, or a parse error; has no context.Context, repositories, DB, network, clock reads, or env; is deterministic and easy to unit-test alone.

Examples: build a prompt from domain events, parse an LLM reply into domain types, turn raw data into domain events, compute totals across entities.

Builders may mint IDs with vo.NewID() and take now as a parameter. Do not import UUID SDKs or call time.Now() inside domain.

The use case only orchestrates I/O: load → call port → hand raw output to a domain pure function → persist. A for/switch that transforms data inside Execute usually belongs in domain. Prompts and domain text stay next to those functions; utils must not import domain/<ctx>.

4. Use case (use_cases/<action>.go, package usecases)

One public method: Execute. One scenario = one <Action>UseCase = one Execute. A second public method is a second use case in its own file. Loops go to worker/; pure helpers go to domain or utils.

Number each scenario step in Execute (// 1. ..., // 2. ...). See section 11.

Input is only domain types. Command/Query fields are vo.ID, status enums, time.Time, typed IDs — never raw string ID / string Status. The api-mapper parses strings before Execute.

Repositories and adapters speak domain types in and out. Mapping stays in mappers, never in the use case.

Return domain entities/results, not DTOs. The api-mapper flattens to DTOs.

Authorize through domain policies (iam.RequireGlobalAdmin(actor), client.RequireWrite(...)), not if role == .... Omit actor only for pre-auth flows (login, forgot-password).

Do not re-check actor == nil inside Execute. authx.Authed already guarantees a non-nil actor. Auth at the API boundary; policies inside for finer checks.

Scenario-only validation uses shared.ErrValidation. If the check must hold for every way to create the entity, put it in domain.

Transactions belong to application: begin/commit via utils/database/ (TxRunner), without seeing pgx.

Time comes from timex.Clock in the constructor (section 9).

Constructor: New<Action>UseCase(deps...). Deps are interfaces (repos, ports, clock).

Background work is also a use case with Execute(ctx) error, driven by worker/.

5. API (api/, package api)

Thin HTTP only.

schema.go — DTOs with Huma tags for syntax (format:"email", minLength, enum, default, …). DTOs are not domain entities; do not accept or return domain.Entity.

endpoints.go — Deps (use cases, config, logger) + Register + one register<Action> per route. Handler shape is always mapper → use case → mapper.

Public: httpx.Handle(...). Authed: authx.Authed(...) (passes actor) or authx.Bearer(...) (token only). Always call the mapper explicitly, even for primitive-only routes, so the shape stays uniform. No business rules, hand-rolled JSON, hand-set statuses (use DefaultStatus for 201/204), or input/output logging (AccessLog already covers it).

OpenAPI: register in utils/openapi via init() in register.go; cmd/openapi-dump imports the module for side effects. Generated specs drive frontend codegen.

Responses go through one envelope (section 7), built by helpers, never by hand.

6. Two mappers

Api-mapper — application/<module>/api/mapper.go.

Input: to<Action>Command / to<Action>Query — raw DTO → typed domain command (UUID→vo.ID, string→status, date→time.Time, normalize, dedup, empty optional → absent).

Output: to<Action>Output — domain → flat DTO.

Parse failures: shared.ErrValidation with the field name → 422 VALIDATION_ERROR.

Pure: args → result, no repo/context/DB. If it starts loading data, it is already a use case.

Do not make domain types Huma-aware (Schema / UnmarshalText on a VO).

Infra-mapper — infrastructure/mappers/: pure Model ↔ Entity. If it needs more than the model and the entity, that logic belongs in domain.

7. Output envelope

Every response is {ok, data?|error?, meta}. The handler returns bare Out/error; httpx/authx wrap it; middleware sets meta.request_id.

Single entity: <Entity>Output, flat json:"snake_case", IDs/enums as strings, dates via apidate, optionals with omitempty / apidate.Optional.

List: <Entity>sOutput{ Items, Total, Limit, Offset }. Always make([]T, 0, n) so Items is [], not null.

Empty success: empty struct + DefaultStatus: http.StatusNoContent.

Error codes are a public contract — do not rename them quietly. One response shape only; no parallel Respond* helpers.

8. Errors

Use cases return plain error. HTTP maps the code.

Base sentinels: domain/shared/errors.go. Context errors: domain/<ctx>/errors.go, wrap a base with %w.

Mapping table in utils/httpx/errors.go: NotFound→404, Conflict→409, Validation→422, Unauthorized→401, Forbidden→403, else→500.

Branch with errors.Is, not error text. Stack traces stay in logs, never in the client body.

9. Time

Only timezone: Europe/Moscow (timex.MSK). No cross-zone conversion in business code.

Do not call time.Now() directly (exception: timex.SystemClock). Use timex.Now() or Clock.Now() from the constructor.

Build calendar times with timex.Date(...), not time.Date(..., UTC/Local).

Use cases that stamp time (audit, tokens, expires_at) take timex.Clock; nil falls back to timex.System(). In domain, timex.Now() is fine for Touch-style methods.

DB: timestamptz / date, not text. API: RFC 3339 / YYYY-MM-DD via timex.

10. Infrastructure and utils

Infrastructure (internal/infrastructure/): models/ — DB rows, stay inside infrastructure. mappers/ — Model ↔ Entity, pure. repositories/<ctx>/ — implements domain/<ctx>/repository.go. adapters/<provider>/ — implements domain/shared/ports/. Boundary in domain types: entities in/out; model mapping stays inside the layer.

Utils (internal/utils/): technical plumbing only, shared across modules and independent of any bounded context. Examples already here: httpx, timex, reqctx, database, pagination, probes, auth, logger, config, redisx, openapi.

What belongs in utils: cross-cutting technical helpers that would make sense in another product with a different domain (HTTP envelope, clocks, DB tx helpers, pagination, auth middleware wiring, logging). They must not import domain/<ctx> or know about business entities, prompts, policies, or scenario rules. The only allowed domain import is domain/shared/errors.go for sentinel→HTTP mapping.

What does not belong in utils: prompts, entity construction, parsing of domain-shaped LLM replies, calculations over business entities, anything that would break if the product’s domain changed. That goes in domain/<ctx>/ as a pure function or entity method. If a helper is only useful inside one application module and is not general plumbing, keep it next to that module (or in domain) instead of promoting it to utils.

Self-check before adding to utils: “could this live in a greenfield service with a totally different business?” Yes → utils. No → domain or the module that needs it.

11. Comments

Code should read without narration. Names carry meaning. Only three comment kinds are allowed:

Numbered steps in use case Execute — mandatory (// 1. ..., // 2. ...). They make the scenario readable and show if HTTP/SQL/parsing leaked in.

Non-obvious SQL inside the query string (tricky JOIN, FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED, special index).

// arrange / // act / // assert in tests.

Remove on sight: comments that restate the next line, section banners, commented-out code, TODOs without a ticket, doc comments that only echo the name. If a name is unclear, rename instead of commenting.

Bad:
func (uc *X) Execute(ctx context.Context, cmd Cmd) (Res, error) {
    user, err := uc.repo.Get(ctx, cmd.ID) // get the user
    if err != nil {
        return Res{}, err // return the error
    }
    user.Activate() // activate
    ...
}

Good:
func (uc *X) Execute(ctx context.Context, cmd Cmd) (Res, error) {
    // 1. Load the user.
    user, err := uc.repo.Get(ctx, cmd.ID)
    if err != nil {
        return Res{}, err
    }
    // 2. Activate — the entity validates its own invariant.
    if err := user.Activate(); err != nil {
        return Res{}, err
    }
    ...
}

12. Tests

Details: docs/development/testing.md.

Focus unit tests on domain/** and use_cases/**. Skip unit-testing infrastructure and Huma handlers; mappers are fine as pure functions.

Stdlib testing only (no testify/mockgen). Black-box <pkg>_test. Table-driven with clear case names. Only arrange/act/assert comments.

Hand-written mocks in mocks_test.go that record calls. If an interface grows too fat, split it instead of adding codegen.

Freeze time with timex.NewFrozen(...). Use database.Noop() for TxRunner. No live time.Now or network in unit tests.

Assert with errors.Is(err, shared.ErrXxx).

Per use case, aim for roughly six branches: forbidden, parse error, not found, domain validation, happy path, repository failure.
